		<ul class='children'>
		<li class="comment byuser comment-author-jessie bypostauthor even depth-2" id="comment-4041">
				<div id="div-comment-4041" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/9cef9c388673aefcda43f6d3c888efb2?s=50&amp;d=identicon&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-50 photo' height='50' width='50' />		<cite class="fn"><a href='http://www.thehungrymouse.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Jessie</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.thehungrymouse.com/2009/06/01/neverending-vanilla-extract-make-your-own/#comment-4041">
			June 3, 2009 at 11:34 am</a>		</div>

		<p>Hey Sarah!</p>
<p>Thanks for stopping by! </p>
<p>I do leave the beans in after adding new ones. I&#8217;m sure that they reach a point where their flavor is spent&#8230;but some of my beans have been in my bottle for years and the extract is just fine.  </p>
<p>I usually top my bottle off once I&#8217;ve used maybe about a third of it. If you wait until your bottle is really empty to add more vodka, you&#8217;ll wind up with a really diluted extract. If you add a little bit here and a little bit there, you won&#8217;t be &#8220;watering&#8221; it down as much, if that makes sense, and you can pretty much keep baking as normal. </p>
<p>Let me know how it goes!</p>
<p>+Jessie</p>

